[ProMED-mail would like to thank John Herbert <j_a_herbert@yahoo.com>,
Niman, Henry L. <HNIMAN@PARTNERS.ORG>, Muruga Vadivale
<vale@pop.jaring.my>, Gerhard Mosbach
<mosbach@web.de> for contributing information on this outbreak.
In this posting we are trying to continue the format of presenting official
reports from Ministries and Departments of Health, the WHO, and physicians
involved in the care and treatment of cases. We are selecting newswire
"shorts" of information of additional suspected cases that have been
reported to the newswires but at the time of preparation of this posting
were not found on official websites. We are very much attempting to
contribute to a rapid dissemination of update information on this unfolding
outbreak without contributing to rumor-mongering.
At present there are no official reports of evidence of widespread
community transmission of SARS. The overwhelming majority of suspected
cases identified to date continue to be in individuals having a history of
close contact (either in the health care environment or among close family
or friends) of other SARS cases. One might interject here that this is one
of the prequalifiers in the case definition: "high fever (greater than 38
C) AND one or more respiratory symptoms including cough, shortness of
breath, difficulty breathing AND one or more of the following: "close
contact* with a person who has been diagnosed with SARS." But the other
qualifier is "recent history of travel to areas reporting cases of SARS"
(<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2003_03_15/en/>) which includes those
countries where cases have been now been confirmed (see [3] Worldwide - WHO
update above).
An etiologic agent has not been identified as yet.
We look forward to learning more about the outbreak in Guangdong China. If
the outbreak in Guangdong is identified as consistent with SARS, may well
have been the "origin" of this syndrome as that outbreak is now described
as having begun in November 2002, several months before the cases were
identified elsewhere.
For those who are more "visually" inclined, the article in the BBC newswire
report at: <http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/2858439.stm> has a nice
map of the world showing the current geographic distribution of where cases
have been reported from. - Mod.MPP]
